    {
      "num": 1,
      "text": "In expert witness testimony regarding fraud examination, which standard governs the admissibility of scientific and technical evidence in U.S. federal courts?",
      "tag": "Expert Witness",
      "options": [
        "A. The Frye standard requiring general acceptance in the relevant scientific community",
        "B. The Daubert standard requiring reliability, relevance, and qualification assessment",
        "C. The Federal Rules of Evidence 803 hearsay exceptions",
        "D. The Kumho standard applying only to non-scientific expert testimony"
      ],
      "correct": 1,
      "justification_correct": "Daubert v. Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals, 509 U.S. 579 (1993) established that Federal Rule of Evidence 702 governs expert testimony admissibility. Courts must assess whether testimony is based on sufficient facts, reliable principles and methods, and whether the expert reliably applied those principles to case facts.",
      "justification_wrong": "Frye was superseded by Daubert in federal courts. FRE 803 addresses hearsay, not expert qualifications. Kumho Tire Co. v. Carmichael extended Daubert to all expert testimony, not just scientific, making it broader than suggested. Daubert remains the controlling federal standard.",
      "difficulty": "EASY",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "law/quiz_001_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 2,
      "text": "In expert witness testimony under Federal Rule of Evidence 702, a fraud examiner must establish daubert reliability. Which factor is LEAST determinative under modern CFE standards when addressing forensic accounting methodology credibility?",
      "tag": "Expert Witness Qualification and Daubert Standards",
      "options": [
        "A. Whether the methodology has been subject to peer review and publication in forensic accounting literature",
        "C. Whether error rates for the specific forensic technique are quantifiable and acceptably low",
        "D. The degree to which the methodology is based on established accounting principles and techniques generally accepted in the discipline",
        "B. The expert's personal certification status and years of practical fraud examination experience"
      ],
      "correct": 3,
      "justification_correct": "Daubert factors (509 U.S. 579) prioritize testability, error rates, peer review, and acceptance. While CFE certification and experience enhance credibility, they are secondary to methodological reliability under FRE 702. Methodology validity supersedes credentials alone.",
      "justification_wrong": "Options A, C, D directly address Daubert's core reliability factors. Peer review, quantifiable error rates, and discipline-accepted principles are primary reliability determinants under contemporary federal evidence standards and CFE guidelines.",
      "difficulty": "HARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "law_cfe/quiz_001_en.json"
    },
    {
      "num": 3,
      "text": "A CFE expert witness is retained by opposing counsel and must testify regarding wire fraud damages in a civil fraud case. Under Federal Rules of Evidence 702 and the Daubert standard, which criterion is most critical for admissibility?",
      "tag": "Expert Witness Qualifications & Daubert",
      "options": [
        "B. Whether the expert's methods and conclusions are reliably grounded in discipline-specific principles",
        "A. The expert's total years of experience in fraud investigations",
        "D. Prior testimony frequency and win rate in similar litigation matters",
        "C. The expert's publication record and peer recognition in academic journals"
      ],
      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "Daubert (509 U.S. 579) and FRE 702 require scientific/technical reliability. Court examines methodology, testability, error rate, and acceptance within relevant field. Reliability—not credentials alone—is gatekeeping standard. ACFE standards support methodology-based expertise.",
      "justification_wrong": "Years of experience, publication record, and litigation history are supplementary factors. Daubert prioritizes methodological rigor over resume credentials. Win rates are irrelevant; reliability of underlying methodology determines admissibility, not trial success rates.",
      "difficulty": "STANDARD",
      "legacy": true,
      "legacy_source": "law_cfe/quiz_001_en.json"
    },
