      "correct": 0,
      "justification_correct": "Daubert v. Merrell Dow Pharmaceuticals, 509 U.S. 579 (1993), requires testability, peer review, error rates, and relevance. However, expert conclusions need not achieve absolute certainty; reasonable degree of professional certainty suffices per FRE 702 and case law (United States v. Hankey, 203 F.3d 1160).",
      "justification_wrong": "Options A, C, and D are Daubert essentials. Testability, peer review, relevance, and transparent reasoning are mandatory gates for expert admissibility. Absolute certainty is not required; forensic work operates within professional standards of reasonable probability and confidence intervals.",
